	<div id="share">
		<ul><li><p id="print"><a href="javascript:window.print();">Print this Page</a></li></ul>
	
	</div>
	
	
	
	
		
			<p>The University of Central Florida&rsquo;s first plug-in hybrid car buzzes around campus with a quiet whir.</p>
<p>It&rsquo;s a greener version of the popular gas and electric-powered hybrids, say team members from UCF&rsquo;s Center for Energy and Sustainability who are working to convert a 2007 Toyota Prius to a plug-in hybrid vehicle for limited all-electric driving.</p>
<p>While today&rsquo;s hybrids are driven by electric motors powered by both batteries and an internal-combustion engine, UCF&rsquo;s plug-in hybrid runs its electric motor on 20 rechargeable 12-volt batteries.</p>
<p>The plug-in will help teach people about energy-saving transportation, both on campus and at energy and sustainability conferences around the state.</p>
<p>Plug-in hybrid cars are already popping up in California and other states, but UCF&rsquo;s newest fleet vehicle is thought to be Florida&rsquo;s first.</p>
<p>&quot;We wanted a fleet vehicle that could act as an icon for the energy and sustainability initiatives that we are working to promote at UCF,&quot; said David Norvell, energy manager for UCF&rsquo;s Center for Energy and Sustainability. &quot;By providing an alternative fuel source separate from gasoline, we are working to decrease our impact on the environment.&quot;</p>
<p><embed src="http://www.youtube.com/p/98770C746242580D" width="530" height="370" type="application/x-shockwave-flash"></embed></p>
<p>After installing the extra batteries, Norvell and his team rewired the Prius&rsquo; computers that switch the car between its gas engine and electric motor. They attached a power cord outside of the trunk that plugs into an electric outlet at night to recharge the batteries.</p>
<p>Touch-screen monitors on the car&rsquo;s console track energy flow and battery levels.</p>
<p>The Prius will run on its electric, battery-powered motor until the car reaches 35 mph &ndash; the posted speed limit on campus. That&rsquo;s when it will it will switch to its gas engine.</p>
<p>Norvell estimates that his group spent about $5,000 on parts to convert the vehicle, compared with a cost of about $15,000 for conversion do-it-yourself kits found online.</p>
<p>The real savings are yet to come, he says, in &quot;fuel&quot; costs and emissions reductions.</p>
<p>Instead of battling rising gas prices, UCF pays about 70 cents to the electric company for the same amount of energy that&rsquo;s in a gallon of gasoline. Energy team members also expect a reduction of about 30 percent in emissions per mile powered by electricity compared with gasoline.</p>
<p>Norvell plans to keep track of the amount of electricity, gas and energy used in his trips on and off campus as researchers and automakers worldwide continue competing to develop fuel-efficient, low-emissions vehicles.</p>
<p>Earlier this year, the Manatee County School District in Bradenton purchased the nation&rsquo;s first two plug-in hybrid school buses. The U.S. Department of Energy recently announced that it would invest nearly $20 million for plug-in hybrid vehicle research and make plug-in hybrids cost-competitive and commercialized by 2016. General Motors this week said it plans to road-test its plug-in Chevrolet Volt early next year.</p>
<p>Meanwhile, Norvell has already showcased UCF&rsquo;s plug-in hybrid car &ndash; with its UCF energy decals &ndash; at several energy and sustainability conferences in Melbourne and Tallahassee this fall.</p>
<p>&quot;It opens up the conversation for energy use all over campus,&quot; said Stacey Radnor, a marketing specialist for the Center for Energy and Sustainability. &quot;When people see the car, they are likely to approach me and ask about energy-efficient and sustainable modes of transportation.&quot;</p>
<hr />
<p><strong>UCF Stands for Opportunity:</strong> Established in 1963, the University of Central Florida is a diverse metropolitan research university that ranks as the 6th-largest in the country with more than 48,000 students. Located in Orlando, Fla., UCF offers high-quality undergraduate and graduate education, student development and continuing education, while conducting cutting-edge research that powers the region's economic development. For more UCF news, visit <a href="index.html">http://news.ucf.edu</a>.</p>
		
	
		
			
		
	
